TypeScript is the primary language for 38% of professional developers. After years of JavaScript codebases drowning in implicit any, the community overcorrected hard. Now you open a PR and find explicit type annotations on every variable, return type decorations on functions that return a plain string, as const scattered like punctuation, and barrel files full of re-exported types that a single file uses.
The best TypeScript code has fewer type annotations than most beginners expect. That is not an opinion: it is what the TypeScript team’s own documentation says. TypeScript’s inference engine is powerful enough that over-annotating does not make code safer. It makes it noisier, harder to refactor, and signals to reviewers that the author does not fully trust the tool.
This article covers five specific patterns to stop using, with before/after examples from a SaaS API service context. It also covers what you genuinely should annotate. The rule of thumb is at the end, but spoiler: annotate at boundaries, trust inference internally.
Stop using React.FC
